Hey everyone! Ms. Duchene will not be doing a read aloud tonight... but she'll be back tomorrow.
She's asking that you instead write notes to elderly people in assisted living homes. They have not been able to have visitors since everything has been closed and I know that they would love to hear from our students! You can email the letters to Miss Duchene at duchene@horizoncolumbus.org and she will make sure they get where they need to go!
Stay healthy, wash your hands, and smile!

post_text:
Here is some information from Mr. Olis with physical activities you can do during this time.

Here are some activities that your students can do at home to stay physically active during this break. The suggested amount of physical activity each day for elementary students is 60 minutes of play.

-our daily warm up activities that include push ups, sit ups, jumping jacks, burpees, arm circles, running in place, marching in place, jumping/ hopping in place.

- knee hockey using a ruler and a soft ball or paper ball

-walking up and down the stairs for extended (1-2 min) periods

-housework/ chores such as cleaning and organizing a room, doing the dishes, wiping down a bathroom

-playing frisbee‚Ä¶

post_text:
HSA Elementary Families,

We are writing to provide you another update on the most current developments and guidance regarding the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic.

As most of you have probably heard, earlier today, Ohio Governor Mike DeWine announced that all K-12 public, private, and charter schools will close at the end of the school day effective, Monday, March 16 for three weeks until April 3.

As a school, Horizon Science Academy Elementary has made the decision to close after school on Friday, March 13 and will reopen after our scheduled Spring Break on April 13

Teachers will be working on creating packets to keep students learning and practicing skills during this‚Ä¶

post_text: What are activity fees for? HSA does field trips with students to re-enforce the general education curriculum. You pay the fee prior to your child 1st field trip then no more money is needed to be sent in the rest of the year for activities! Each child has the opportunity for 2 in school field trips (COSI on Wheels and the Archaeological Historical Society), a fall, a spring, a group field trip and a tye dye shirt for field day. Activity fees for the 2019-2020 school year are $50/child

post_text:
Summer reading is important for your child‚Äôs academic growth. Make sure your child gets lots of sunshine, play and READING TIME!!!

Your student has a chance to participate in our summer reading program and earn prizes for their summer reading. Check your student's book bag for their "Around the World" and "Out of this World" Adventure reading log. Complete the reading log and Bingo card to win prizes. Logs are to be turned in next year to your homeroom teacher in the first week of school. Use your reading log minutes at Columbus Metro Libraries to win prizes as well. Visit your local library to find out more.

post_text: Students played outside with different activities as their rewards for Positive behavioral interventions and supports! (PBIS) is a way for schools to encourage good behavior. With PBIS, schools teach kids about behavior, just as they would teach about other subjects like reading or math. The focus of PBIS is prevention, not punishment.

School Days
by:Lenore Hetrick
Spelling and writing and reading,
and then a game we play.
Then reading, and writing and spelling,
and to our lunch we're away.

Then writing, and spelling, and reading,
we student the rest of the day.
So goes school from September,
until the month of May.

We hope everyone is having a restful winter break filled with making memories with family and friends. School will resume on Tuesday, January 8. We look forward to seeing everyone back to school.

The second quarter ends this Friday and Quarter 3 will begin on Monday, January 14.

There are no clubs or tutoring this week.

This Friday, January 11 is a jeans day for a $1. Students may also wear purple shirts for an additional dollar. Money raised will go towards CYSP activities for students.

text:
We hope everyone is having a restful winter break filled with making memories with family and friends. School will resume on Tuesday, January 8. We look forward to seeing everyone back to school.

The second quarter ends this Friday and Quarter 3 will begin on Monday, January 14.

There are no clubs or tutoring this week.

This Friday, January 11 is a jeans day for a $1. Students may also wear purple shirts for an additional dollar. Money raised will go towards CYSP activities for students.

On Saturday, January 12 there is CYSP Saturday School.
